songs.song: La La La (made popular by Naughty Boy ft. Sam Smith) [vocal version]
songs.comment_text:
This song tells the history of a Bolivian legend. The kid is deaf and runs away from his abusive father. In his way he finds the dog, and helps a old man (in the legend, bullies were hitting him) then, both of them find a guy who was in a satanic cult but  deserted. Now, "el t√≠o" (translates to "uncle" but represents satan,in Bolivian culture)  disfigured his face as punishment, which is why he covers it. They go to the mines caves where  "el tio" lives (in the city of Oruro), legend says that with his singing of hatred people get corrupted and kill each other.

It's then when the old man,the dog and the guy with the mask say goodbye to the kid, because they couldn't enter the cave without being corrupted. The kid is immune because of his deafness and he begins to sing to el Tio, in order to keep him calm for the whole eternity and prevent more people to hear his singing of hatred

I am from Bolivia, in the city where this was filmed (La Paz), i like this video and i wanted to share the legend with you!

Edit: after 7 years I decided to edit this comment to convey the story with a better English, thx to all for their kind messages over the yearsüíö I'll leave the previous version below just as a good memory to look at, hope it doesn't bother.

This song its about a legend from Bolivia (a latin country) the kid is deaf and his father is bad,so the kid run away. He finds the dog, and help a old man (en the legend,a bullies were hitting him) then, both of them find a guy who was in a satanic group but he desert and "el t√≠o" (satan,in Bolivian culture)  disfigurement his face,thats why hi is cover it. They go to the cave of "el tio" and the legend said that "el tio" sing all the feelings of hate and that kind of thing,and the people get corrupted and kill each other. Its then when the old man,the dog and the guy with a mask say goodbye to the kid, so as not to get corrupted they leave. And the kid stay, because he is deaf so he cant get corrupted,and he begans to sing to "el tio" to keep him calm for the whole eternity 

I am from Bolivia, in the city were this was filmed, i like this video and i wanted to share the legend with you, sorry if I have a bad english,in the best i can do :)

songs.post_title: Best Songs for Loss and Grief
songs.comment_text:
Dear Jelly Roll,

I am a Navy combat veteran. I felt compelled to reach out to you after listening to your song "I'm Not OK," which touched me in a way no other song has.

As someone who has faced the harsh realities of combat and now copes with the challenges of a traumatic brain injury (TBI) and PTSD, I've often found it incredibly difficult to articulate the whirlwind of emotions that accompany these experiences. The pain, the memories, and the ongoing struggles with mental health are hard for many around me to understand. Your song, however, captures these feelings with a raw honesty that truly hits home.

"I'm Not OK" speaks to the silent battles many of us face long after the visible wounds have healed. It's a powerful reminder that it's alright to not be alright, and that we are not alone in our struggles. The lyrics and your soulful delivery offer a sense of solidarity and understanding that is incredibly comforting.

Thank you for creating a piece of music that not only acknowledges but validates the emotions of those of us who have walked a difficult path. Your music serves as a beacon of hope and a reminder that there is strength in vulnerability.

I wanted to express my heartfelt gratitude for your work. Your music has made a significant impact on my life and, I am sure, on the lives of many others. Please continue to create and share your gift with the world.

With deepest appreciation, 
Chris Gentleman

songs.post_title: Best Songs for Loss and Grief
songs.comment_text:
I had a roommate in college... he got burned really badly.  Scars all over half of his face.  People always asked him what happened, and he never told the same story twice.  Me?  I never asked him what happened.  I never treated him like he was anything other than a human being.

We were roommates for three years.  The year he was graduating, he came to me and said I was the only person who never asked him what happened, and who never looked at him funny.  He said he had mad respect for that, and he told me the real story.

It was awful, and it's not my place to share it.  But let it be a lesson.  It doesn't matter what we look like on the outside... inside, we're still human beings.

songs.post_title: Best Songs for Loss and Grief
songs.comment_text: My journey in music has staggering highs and lows. I have seasons where I feel like I can‚Äôt miss, where I feel quite literally invincible. Then there are seasons where I wonder if I will ever write anything true or special again, whether I have anything to offer, whether I have simply fooled everyone up to this point. I am a positive guy but that just means that I go to war with my head when these doubts attack. The smile is often a smile through some sort of intense struggle. This is normal. This is everyone. If you hear this song and it inspires you to not give up on someone or better yet yourself I am with you. I am vulnerable, weak, unsure, while also being stubborn, hopeful, and optimistic. It‚Äôs a package deal. Keep telling me in the comments someone you haven‚Äôt given up on. Reading these comments is feeding my soul.

songs.comment_text:
This brings back happy childhood memories for me, especially of watching the TV performances of the fabulous Eartha Kitt. What a woman! She had suffered so much hurt in her early life, yet she never played the part of the 'pity me' wilting flower. 
Whether she was singing, acting, or being interviewed, Ms Kitt wielded her immense feminine power so expertly; she was intelligent, strong, sexy, glamorous and she had a delicious sense of humour. She was also the, 'purrr-fect' catwoman, and it's no wonder that she was a beloved and very popular entertainer, appealing to men, women and children.
Rest in peace, lovely lady.

I have rekindled the love of the music hall once again. After watching many episodes from yesteryear. Thank you so much for uploading these "gem's of television" for my memories to feast on. I was lucky enough to get tickets at the time for myself, wife and in-laws, and can't remember having a sensation like it since. The pleasure and happiness of singing along and laughing at so many acts, with household names topping the bill.
Some one mentioned in the comments of bring it back, unfortunately I can't imagine present comedians being any good as they rely too much on shocking, mocking,  effing and swearing in short they are crass.
I urge anyone anywhere any age to watch as many as possible to see true and ultra talented show people at their highest quality output. Truth is I should have been born 80yrs before my time.
Please join me in a chorus of down at the old bull and bush.
Good bye and God bless.
